      <h2>What Self-Employment Tax Really Costs You — and How to Reduce It</h2>
      <p>Freelancers and independent contractors are often caught off guard by self-employment tax — not because the rate is a secret, but because W-2 employees never see their half of it on their paystub. If you're self-employed, you pay both halves of Social Security and Medicare. Here's what your estimate means and what you can do about it.</p>

      <h3>Why Self-Employment Tax Surprises People</h3>
      <p>When you're employed, your employer pays half of FICA (7.65%) and you pay the other half through payroll withholding. As a self-employed person, you pay the full 15.3% — 12.4% for Social Security (up to the wage base) and 2.9% for Medicare. That's on top of your regular income tax. Many first-year freelancers end up owing thousands they didn't budget for.</p>

      <h3>How to Interpret Your SE Tax Estimate — Step by Step</h3>
      <ol class="guide-steps">
        <li><strong>Note the net earnings figure, not gross revenue.</strong> SE tax is calculated on 92.35% of your net self-employment income (gross revenue minus business expenses). The 7.65% reduction approximates the employer-side deduction W-2 employees get automatically.</li>
        <li><strong>Understand the deductible half.</strong> You can deduct 50% of your SE tax when calculating your adjusted gross income (AGI). This deduction reduces your regular income tax — not your SE tax itself. The calculator shows this deduction separately so you can factor it into your full tax picture.</li>
        <li><strong>Add SE tax to your income tax estimate.</strong> SE tax and regular federal income tax are separate obligations. Use this calculator for SE tax, then use our <a href="/income-tax-calculator">income tax calculator</a> for the income tax portion. Your total federal tax burden is both combined.</li>
        <li><strong>Check the Social Security wage base.</strong> In 2025, the Social Security portion (12.4%) only applies to the first $176,100 of net self-employment income. Above that, only the 2.9% Medicare portion applies (plus the 0.9% Additional Medicare Tax if your income exceeds $200,000 single / $250,000 married).</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>3 Common Mistakes When Using This Calculator</h3>
      <div class="mistakes-list">
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <div class="mistake-number">1</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Entering gross revenue instead of net profit.</strong> SE tax is on profit, not revenue. Subtract your legitimate business expenses first — equipment, software, home office, mileage, health insurance premiums — then enter the net figure.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <div class="mistake-number">2</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Forgetting to make quarterly estimated payments.</strong> If you expect to owe more than $1,000 in SE + income tax, the IRS requires quarterly payments. Missing them triggers underpayment penalties. See our <a href="/quarterly-estimated-taxes">estimated tax guide</a> for deadlines and how to calculate payments.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <div class="mistake-number">3</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Not tracking deductible business expenses.</strong> Every dollar of legitimate business expense reduces your net profit and therefore your SE tax. Common missed deductions include home office, health insurance premiums, retirement contributions (SEP-IRA, Solo 401k), and the self-employed health insurance deduction.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>What to Do Next</h3>
      <ul class="next-steps">
        <li>Calculate your full federal tax picture: use this SE tax estimate alongside our <a href="/income-tax-calculator">income tax calculator</a> — add both results together for your total federal liability.</li>
        <li>Set up quarterly estimated payments using the deadlines and worksheet in our <a href="/quarterly-estimated-taxes">estimated tax guide</a>.</li>
        <li>Read the <a href="/self-employment-tax-rate-2025">self-employment tax rate page</a> for a complete breakdown of the 15.3% rate, the wage base, and the Additional Medicare Tax threshold.</li>
        <li>If your SE income is significant, explore SEP-IRA or Solo 401(k) contributions — they reduce your taxable income and are explained in our <a href="/401k-contribution-limits-2025">retirement contribution limits guide</a>.</li>
      </ul>

