  <!-- How It Works — FIXED: plain English replacing jargon-heavy original -->
  <section class="how-it-works">
    <div class="how-toggle">How It Works</div>
    <div class="how-content">

      <h2>How Self-Employment Tax Is Calculated</h2>
      <p>Unlike W-2 employees, self-employed individuals are responsible for both halves of Social Security and Medicare tax. Here's how the math works.</p>

      <div class="steps-grid">
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">1</div>
          <h3>Calculate Your Net Profit</h3>
          <p>Subtract your business expenses from your gross 1099 income. SE tax is owed on profit — not on total revenue. Legitimate expenses like equipment, software, and home office reduce what you owe.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">2</div>
          <h3>Apply the 92.35% Rule</h3>
          <p>The IRS calculates SE tax on 92.35% of your net profit — not 100%. This adjustment accounts for the fact that employees only pay tax on the employee share of FICA, not the employer share.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">3</div>
          <h3>Calculate Social Security and Medicare Tax</h3>
          <p>Social Security tax is 12.4% on net earnings up to $176,100 (the 2025 wage base). Medicare tax is 2.9% on all net earnings with no cap. Together they equal the 15.3% SE tax rate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <div class="step-num">4</div>
          <h3>Claim Your Deduction at Tax Time</h3>
          <p>When you file your Form 1040, you can deduct exactly half of your total SE tax as an above-the-line adjustment to income. This reduces your taxable income for federal income tax purposes — a built-in benefit for self-employed filers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula-label">Formula Reference</div>
        <pre><code>// Net Profit
Net Profit          = Gross 1099 Income - Business Expenses

// SE Taxable Income
SE Taxable Income   = Net Profit x 92.35%

// SE Tax
Social Security Tax = SE Taxable Income x 12.4%  (up to $176,100)
Medicare Tax        = SE Taxable Income x 2.9%
Total SE Tax        = Social Security Tax + Medicare Tax

// Above-the-Line Deduction
Deductible Half     = Total SE Tax x 50%</code></pre>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

